Everyone creates with passion, anon; you downplay the efforts of people with as much self-doubt and abysmal senses of self-worth as other creatives when you reduce those who draw in obscurity to dispassionate dregs because they're not as... "inherently motivated" as the artists who have enjoyed some measure of visibility from their first sketches to now. Yes, artists who receive attention (even from sympathetic artists) are going to be more motivated to practice than those who are completely ignored. This is true of writers as well.

We're social creatures, whether online - or outside, bumping & grinding over a bed of freshly mowed grass - is inconsequential. Passion impels creativity, but it's an internal mover; the impetus to practice and pursue artistic milestones is based on a process of risk (time spent in practice) begetting an external reward, which attention serves because we're social animals anyway - it's in our nature. One's value in drawing appreciates convertibly with experimentation, which is blocked in with positive reinforcement. Without positive reinforcement, your nascent drawing talent is going to stagnate and risk fizzling out entirely, or leave for a community that's more evenly reciprocal.
